1. Write a program in Java that computes the areas of Circle, Triangle, and Rectangle using Compile-Time polymorphism.
Note: Compile-time polymorphism (Method Overloading) requires methods to have the same name but different parameter lists. Since Triangle and Rectangle both usually take two double values, I’ve differentiated them by using a float for the Triangle parameters to ensure the signatures are unique.

public class AreaCalculate {

    // Rectangle: Two doubles
    public void calculateArea(double length, double width) {
        double area = length * width;
        System.out.println("Area of Rectangle: " + area);
    }

    // Triangle: Two floats (to distinguish from Rectangle)
    public void calculateArea(float base, float height) {
        double area = 0.5 * base * height;
        System.out.println("Area of Triangle: " + area);
    }

    // Circle: One double
    public void calculateArea(double radius) {
        double area = Math.PI * radius * radius;
        System.out.println("Area of Circle: " + area);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        AreaCalculate myArea = new AreaCalculate();
        
        myArea.calculateArea(5.0);            // Calls Circle
        myArea.calculateArea(10.0, 4.0);      // Calls Rectangle
        myArea.calculateArea(6.0f, 8.0f);     // Calls Triangle
    }
}

2. Write a program in Java that computes the areas of Circle, Triangle, and Rectangle using Run-Time polymorphism.
Note: Run-time polymorphism (Method Overriding) uses Inheritance. The parent class defines the method, and each subclass provides its own specific implementation.

class Shape {
    public void calculateArea() {
        System.out.println("Area calculation not defined for generic shape.");
    }
}

class Rectangle extends Shape {
    private double length, width;
    Rectangle(double length, double width) {
        this.length = length;
        this.width = width;
    }
    @Override
    public void calculateArea() {
        System.out.println("Area of Rectangle: " + (length * width));
    }
}

class Triangle extends Shape {
    private double base, height;
    Triangle(double base, double height) {
        this.base = base;
        this.height = height;
    }
    @Override
    public void calculateArea() {
        System.out.println("Area of Triangle: " + (0.5 * base * height));
    }
}

class Circle extends Shape {
    private double radius;
    Circle(double radius) {
        this.radius = radius;
    }
    @Override
    public void calculateArea() {
        System.out.println("Area of Circle: " + (Math.PI * radius * radius));
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Shape myShape;

        myShape = new Circle(5.0);
        myShape.calculateArea(); 

        myShape = new Rectangle(10.0, 4.0);
        myShape.calculateArea(); 

        myShape = new Triangle(6.0, 8.0);
        myShape.calculateArea(); 
    }
}

3. Write a program in Java to implement abstraction using "Person" and "Employee" classes.
Note: By making Person abstract, we hide the general concept of a person and only expose the specific implementation (Employee).

abstract class Person {
    private String name;
    private int age;

    public Person(String name, int age) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
    }

    // Abstract method: Hidden detail to be implemented by subclass
    public abstract void displayDetails();

    // Regular getters
    public String getName() { return name; }
    public int getAge() { return age; }
}

class Employee extends Person {
    private String employeeId;

    public Employee(String name, int age, String employeeId) {
        super(name, age);
        this.employeeId = employeeId;
    }

    @Override
    public void displayDetails() {
        System.out.println("Employee ID: " + employeeId);
        System.out.println("Name: " + getName());
        System.out.println("Age: " + getAge());
    }
}

public class AbstractionDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // We cannot instantiate 'Person' directly, hiding its internal details.
        Person emp = new Employee("John Doe", 30, "E123");
        emp.displayDetails();
    }
}
